### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.

This is more of an idea, to get the `LinearOperator` interface cleaner and provide more control to the user. Original comment: https://github.com/scipy/scipy/pull/23836#issuecomment-3902233813

See also:
- https://github.com/scipy/scipy/issues/24611
- https://github.com/scipy/scipy/issues/24613

### Describe the solution you'd like.

I will focus on `matmat`, but the same holds true for `matvec`, but for that see also https://github.com/scipy/scipy/issues/24611

Currently, the linear operator interface is founded on the methods `matmat` and `rmatmat` which implement `A @ x` and `A.H @ x`, where `A.H` denotes the hermitian adjoint. But in addition, the `LinearOperator` interface also provide the transposed `A.T`, which is not represented by any specific function and is always given by the default implementation which looks like
```python
class _TransposedLinearOperator(LinearOperator):
       def _matmat(self, x):
               # NB. np.conj works also on sparse matrices
               return np.conj(self.A._rmatmat(np.conj(x)))
       <...>
```
The only way to change the behavior of the transposed is by sub-classing `LinearOperator` and manually overwriting `._transpose()`. I see two problems with that, first this implementation relies heavily on `numpy` and it feels a bit like a hack that `numpy` functions actually do work on `scipy.sparray` as well. But more problematic in my opinion is, that there is no intended way for the user to directly provide a implementation for the transposed (as `rmatmat` is for the adjoint).

I would suggest, to extend the `LinearOperator` interface to distinguish between the adjoint and transposed and provide separate implementations for each. With that at in mind, i think it would be very useful to further extend the `LinearOperator` framework to also provide a method `conjugate()` returning the complex conjugate of the operator`

So, i suggest, that the `LinearOperator` interface core consisting of `matmat` and `rmatmat` is replaced by

- `matmat`: implements `A @ x` (corresponds to current `matmat`)
- `cmatmat`: implements `A.C @ x`, with `A.C` denoting the complex conjugate of `A`, can be provided by a default implementation
- `tmatmat`: implements `A.T @ x`, with `A.T` denoting the transposed of `A`, can be provided by a default implementation if `ctmatmat` is given
- `ctmatmat`: implements `A.H @ x` with `A.H = A.C.T` denoting the complex conjugate transposed / hermitian adjoint of `A`, can be provided by  a default implementation if `tmatmat` is given (corresponds to the current `rmatmat`)

Ignoring for now `shape`, `dtype` as well as products and sums of `LinearOperator`s, just focusing on the core mechanic, a frame for such an implementation of the `LinearOperator` interface could look like the following:

```python
from abc import abstractmethod

class LinearOperator:

    def matmat(self, other):
        if isinstance(other, LinearOperator):
            return _ProductLinearOperator(self, other)
        else:
            return self._matmat(other)

    @abstractmethod    
    def _matmat(self, other):
        ...

    def _cmatmat(self, other):
        # default implementation of _matmat for _ConjugateLinearOperator
        # .conjugate() is available for numpy arrays, scipy sparse matrices
        return self._matmat(other.conjugate()).conjugate()

    def _tmatmat(self, other):
        # default implementation of _matmat for _TransposedLinearOperator
        if type(self)._ctmatmat == LinearOperator._ctmatmat:
            raise NotImplementedError("Please implement _tmatmat or _ctmatmat.")
        # .conjugate() is available for numpy arrays, scipy sparse matrices
        return self._ctmatmat(other.conjugate()).conjugate()

    def _ctmatmat(self, other):
        # default implementation of _matmat for _AdjointLinearOperator
        if type(self)._tmatmat == LinearOperator._tmatmat:
            raise NotImplementedError("Please implement _tmatmat or _ctmatmat.")
        # .conjugate() is available for numpy arrays, scipy sparse matrices
        return self._tmatmat(other.conjugate()).conjugate()

    _T = None
    def transpose(self):
        if self._T is None: self._T = self._transpose()
        return self._T

    _H = None
    def adjoint(self):
        if self._H is None: self._H = self._adjoint()
        return self._H

    _C = None
    def conjugate(self):
        if self._C is None: self._C = self._conjugate()
        return self._C

    T = property(transpose)
    H = property(adjoint)
    C = property(conjugate)

    def _transpose(self):
        return _TransposedLinearOperator(self)
    def _adjoint(self):
        return _AdjointLinearOperator(self)
    def _conjugate(self):
        return _ConjugateLinearOperator(self)


class _TransposedLinearOperator(LinearOperator):

    def __init__(self, linop: LinearOperator):
        self.linop = linop

    def _matmat(self, other):
        return self.linop._tmatmat(other)

    def _transpose(self):
        return self.linop
    def _adjoint(self):
        return self.linop.conjugate()
    def _conjugate(self):
        return self.linop.adjoint()


class _AdjointLinearOperator(LinearOperator):

    def __init__(self, linop: LinearOperator):
        self.linop = linop

    def _matmat(self, other):
        return self.linop._ctmatmat(other)

    def _transpose(self):
        return self.linop.conjugate()
    def _adjoint(self):
        return self.linop
    def _conjugate(self):
        return self.linop.transpose()


class _ConjugateLinearOperator(LinearOperator):

    def __init__(self, linop: LinearOperator):
        self.linop = linop

    def _matmat(self, other):
        return self.linop._cmatmat(other)

    def _transpose(self):
        return self.linop.adjoint()
    def _adjoint(self):
        return self.linop.transpose()
    def _conjugate(self):
        return self.linop


class _CustomLinearOperator(LinearOperator):

    def __init__(self, matmat, ctmatmat=None, cmatmat=None, tmatmat=None):
        self._matmat = matmat
        if ctmatmat is not None:
            self._ctmatmat = ctmatmat
        if cmatmat is not None:
            self._cmatmat = cmatmat
        if tmatmat is not None:
            self._tmatmat = tmatmat


class MatrixLinearOperator(LinearOperator):

    def __init__(self, A):
        self.A = A

    def _matvec(self, x):
        return self.A @ x

    def _transpose(self):
        return MatrixLinearOperator(self.A.transpose())

    def _conjugate(self):
        return MatrixLinearOperator(self.A.conjugate())

    def _adjoint(self):
        return MatrixLinearOperator(self.A.conjugate().transpose())
```

The final user-interface for a `LinearOperator` then reads

- `.matmat` or `@` for the application of the operator, e.g. `A @ x`
- `.transpose()` or `.T` for a `LinearOperator` representing the transposed, e.g. `A.T @ x`
- `.adjoint()` or `.H` for a `LinearOperator` representing the adjoint, e.g. `A.H @ x`
- `.conjugate()` or `.C` for a `LinearOperator` representing the comlex conjugate, e.g. `A.C @ x`

To define a new operator, the user could either use `_CustomLinearOperator` and provide `matmat` (mandatory), `cmatmat` (purely optional), `tmatmat` and/or `ctmatmat` (at least one needed for defining the adjoint and transposed).
Alternatively, the user could subclass `LinearOperator` and overwrite `_matmat` (mandatory) as well as a) `_cmatmat`, `_tmatmat` and `_ctmatmat` (same necessity as in `_CustomLinearOperator`) or b) directly overwrite `_conjugate`, `_transpose` and `_adjoint`.

I think that approach has several benefits:

- more functionality with the new `.conjugate()` method
- more optional user-control by specifying the conjugate, transposed and adjoint separately, 
- without forcing more user-input (the only mandatory is still `matmat` and for full functionality a single second argument is needed, either `ctmatmat` (which corresponds to the current second `rmatmat`) or `tmatmat`).
- cleaner implementation (personal opinion)
- cleaner error handling (even when calling something like `A.H.T.T.C.H @ x`) as there are not actually several adjoints, transposeds and conjugates formed, passing around methods completely obscuring what missing functionality in `A` causes an error.


